Author Biographies
Laura E. VanderDrift is an assistant professor of psychology at 
Syracuse University. Her research interests include the predictors 
of outcomes within interdependent social relationships, including 
dissolution behaviors and health outcomes.
Kevin M. Antshel is an associate professor of psychology and 
director of the Clinical Psychology Doctoral Program at Syracuse 
University. His research focuses on better understanding the het-
erogeneity of ADHD with particular emphasis on mediators and 
moderators of treatment outcomes.
Amy K. Olszewski is an adjunct instructor of psychology at 
Syracuse University. Her research focuses on developmental 
neuropsychology.

## Results
Results: ADHD symptoms were associated with greater relationship 
difficulties. In both samples, inattentive symptoms were associated with greater interest in relational alternatives and less 
constructive responses to partner’s bad behaviors, whereas hyperactive-impulsive symptoms were associated with negative 
responses to bad behavior.

## Clinical Significance
Conclusion: The results of this study have implications for developing cognitive-behavioral 
therapy interventions targeting relationship difficulties in young adults with ADHD. (J. of Att. Dis. XXXX; XX(X) XX-XX)
Keywords
ADHD, hyperactivity, impulsivity, inattention, romantic relationships, relationship maintenance
